            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this Section 179 deduction calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator helps you estimate how much of your equipment,
                vehicle, and software purchases you may be able to expense
                immediately under
                <strong>Section 179</strong> and
                <strong>bonus depreciation</strong>, and how much basis remains
                for regular MACRS depreciation.
              </p>

              <h3>Key assumptions</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  All assets entered are qualifying Section 179 and/or bonus
                  property under current law.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Business use percentage is at least 50% for assets you mark as
                  Section 179 eligible.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Illustrative annual limits are used; always confirm the
                  official IRS limits for your filing year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Vehicle luxury auto caps, listed property recapture, and
                  special elections are not modeled in detail.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Section 179 vs. bonus depreciation vs. MACRS</h2>
              <p>
                When you buy qualifying business property, you generally have
                three layers of potential deductions in the first year:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Section 179 expensing</strong> – elective, subject to
                  dollar, phase‑out, and income limits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Bonus depreciation</strong> – automatic (unless you
                  elect out), applied to remaining basis of eligible property.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Regular MACRS depreciation</strong> – applied to any
                  basis left after Section 179 and bonus.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>1. Section 179 dollar limit and phase‑out</h3>
              <p>
                Section 179 lets you elect to expense up to an annual dollar
                limit. That limit is reduced dollar‑for‑dollar when your total
                cost of qualifying property placed in service exceeds a
                phase‑out threshold.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Effective Section 179 limit</strong></p>
                <p>
                  If total qualifying property cost ≤ phase‑out threshold:<br />
                  &nbsp;&nbsp;Effective limit = statutory dollar limit
                </p>
                <p>
                  If total qualifying property cost &gt; phase‑out threshold:<br />
                  &nbsp;&nbsp;Effective limit = max(0, statutory dollar limit −
                  (total cost − phase‑out threshold))
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Business income limitation</h3>
              <p>
                Section 179 deduction is also limited to your
                <strong>taxable business income</strong> from all active trades
                or businesses. The calculator compares:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Effective Section 179 dollar limit (after phase‑out), and
                </li>
                <li>Your business income input,</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                and uses the <strong>smaller</strong> of the two as your maximum
                current‑year Section 179 deduction.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Allocation of Section 179 across assets</h3>
              <p>
                For simplicity, this tool allocates the allowable Section 179
                deduction <strong>pro‑rata</strong> across all assets you marked
                as Section 179‑eligible, based on their business basis:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Business basis per asset</strong> = Cost × (Business
                  use % ÷ 100)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Pro‑rata Section 179 for an asset</strong> = Business
                  basis × (Total allowable Section 179 ÷ Sum of all Section
                  179‑eligible bases)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                In real life, you can choose which assets to expense first. If
                you are planning a specific strategy (e.g., expensing
                short‑lived assets first), adjust your inputs or consult a tax
                professional.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Bonus depreciation</h3>
              <p>
                After Section 179, the calculator applies a
                <strong>bonus depreciation percentage</strong> to the remaining
                basis of assets you marked as bonus‑eligible. The bonus
                percentage can vary by year under current law.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Bonus basis</strong> = Business basis − Section 179
                  allocated
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Bonus deduction</strong> = Bonus basis × Bonus rate
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Remaining MACRS basis</strong> = Bonus basis − Bonus
                  deduction
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Practical planning tips</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Time purchases carefully.</strong> Property must be
                  placed in service (not just ordered) during the tax year to
                  qualify.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Watch the 50% business‑use rule.</strong> Falling
                  below 50% business use in later years can trigger recapture.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consider future income.</strong> If current‑year
                  income is low, you may prefer bonus depreciation (not
                  income‑limited) or regular MACRS.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Vehicles are special.</strong> Passenger autos and
                  SUVs have additional caps and exceptions; heavy vehicles may
                  qualify for larger deductions.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Disclaimer</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is for
                <strong>educational and planning purposes only</strong>. It
                simplifies many aspects of the tax law and does not replace
                professional advice. Section 179 and bonus depreciation rules
                change over time and can interact with other provisions (such as
                listed property, at‑risk rules, and passive activity
                limitations).
              </p>
              <p>
                Always review your specific situation with a qualified tax
                professional and consult the latest IRS guidance, including
                <em>Publication 946</em> and the instructions for Form 4562.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about Section 179</h2>

              <h3>What types of property can qualify for Section 179?</h3>
              <p>
                In general, Section 179 applies to
                <strong>tangible personal property</strong> used more than 50%
                in an active trade or business, including:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Machinery and equipment</li>
                <li>Computers, servers, and office equipment</li>
                <li>Off‑the‑shelf computer software</li>
                <li>
                  Certain improvements to non‑residential real property (e.g.,
                  roofs, HVAC, fire protection, security systems)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Land, buildings, and property used for lodging usually do
                <strong>not</strong> qualify, with limited exceptions.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use Section 179 for used equipment?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Section 179 can apply to both
                <strong>new and used</strong> qualifying property, as long as it
                is new to you and meets all other requirements.
              </p>

              <h3>What happens if I exceed the Section 179 limits?</h3>
              <p>
                If your desired Section 179 deduction exceeds the
                <strong>dollar limit</strong>, the
                <strong>phase‑out</strong> threshold, or your
                <strong>business income</strong>, the excess amount is generally
                carried forward to future years, subject to the limits in those
                years.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I actually claim the deduction?</h3>
              <p>
                Section 179 and bonus depreciation are claimed on
                <strong>Form 4562, Depreciation and Amortization</strong>, filed
                with your tax return. Your tax software or preparer will use
                your asset details to complete the form.
              </p>
